value.value: Diabetes mellitus caused by activating mutation(s) in genes (KNCJ11 and/or ABCC8) encoding either of the 2 proteins (Kir6.2 and/or SUR1) that make up the pancreatic beta cell adenosine triphosphate-sensitive potassium channel, which is crucial for the regulation of glucose-induced insulin secretion.
K ATP channel-associated neonatal diabetes mellitus that does not resolve spontaneously.

Decreased activity of hexose-6-phosphatase due to autosomal recessive mutation(s) in the H6PD gene. This enzyme is necessary to generate NADPH, a cofactor in the 11-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase pathway required for conversion of cortisone to cortisol. The condition is characterized by hyperandrogenism as a result of increased adrenocorticotropic hormone stimulation of the adrenal gland due to failure of cortisol-mediated down-regulation, and is clinically indistinguishable from 11-beta HSD type 1 deficiency.
A small, round cell found in the lower part of the epidermis of the taste bud. It differentiates into a new receptor cell and renewed about every 10 days.
Supranormal concentration of thyroxine in the blood.

An autosomal recessive disorder caused by loss-of-function mutation(s) in the GALNT3, FGF23, or KL gene, which encode polypeptide N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferase 3, fibroblast growth factor 23, and klotho, respectively. This condition, the biochemical hallmark of which is hyperphosphatemia caused by increased renal phosphate absorption, is characterized by the progressive deposition of calcium phosphate crystals in periarticular spaces, soft tissues, and/or bone.
Hyperthyroidism, the cause of which is present at birth.

A genetic condition caused by loss-of-function mutation(s) in the CASR gene, encoding extracellular calcium-sensing receptor. It is characterized by severe hypercalcemia and metabolic bone disease occurring in the first six months of life.

A condition in which hypoglycemia is accompanied by ketosis. This condition may be a manifestation of another condition such as glycogen storage disease, ketone utilization defects, growth hormone deficiency, or cortisol deficiency.
Ketotic hypoglycemia that usually occurs in young, thin children in association with infection or fasting, and which typically resolves by age 6-8 years.
Hypoparathyroidism resulting from medical treatment or intervention.

label.value: Hypogonadotropic Hypogonadism with Adrenal Hypoplasia Congenita

value.value: Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism with congenital adrenal hypoplasia associated with mutation(s) in the NR0B1 gene (on the X chromosome).
Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism in association with an impaired sense of smell.
Diabetes mellitus caused by mutation(s) in mitochondrial DNA.

A-DNA is a shorter and wider helix than B-DNA. Most RNA and RNA-DNA duplex are in this form. While deep, narrow major groove is not easily accessible to proteins but wide, shallow minor groove is accessible to proteins but with lower information content than major groove. A-DNA is the favored conformation at low water concentrations. Base pairs are tilted to helix axis and displaced from axis and sugar pucker is C3'-endo (in RNA 2'-OH inhibits C2'-endo conformation). When examined from the top of the helix, there is a large hole in the middle, the sugar phosphate backbone is at the edge of the helix, and the bases are displaced towards the edge.
Iodine-induced hyperthyroidism.

A bone disorder caused by autosomal recessive mutation(s) of the gene TNFRSF11B, which encodes tumor necrosis factor receptor superfamily member 11B. This condition is characterized by excessive osteoclastic resorption of bone followed by deposition of weak, disorganized woven bone. Clinical characteristics include short stature, enlarged skull, bony deformities, bone pain, warm skin over the affected bone, joint stiffness, headaches, hearing loss, and elevated serum alkaline phosphatase.

Ovarian dysfunction due to a defect at the receptor or post receptor level, or due to the presence of antibodies against gonadotropin receptors, resulting in deficient gonadotropin signaling that causes elevated concentrations of follicle stimulating hormone and/or luteinizing hormone. A distinguishing feature is the presence of normal numbers of ova.
Contrasexual pubertal development caused by medical intervention.

Conditions affecting individuals whose karyotype is 46,XY that is characterized by atypical development of the internal or external sex structures, or the gonads, and in whom no genetic, environmental, or biochemical causation can be established.
Subnormal concentration of luteinizing hormone.
A subtype of micronodular adrenal hyperplasia, characterized by multiple non-pigmented nodules.

An autosomal recessive or sporadic form of adrenal hypoplasia congenita frequently associated with central nervous system anomalies including anencephaly and pituitary defects. Histologically the adrenal gland is distinguished by the absence of fetal adrenal cortex and the presence of a small amount of normal, permanent adult adrenal cortex.

A form of metaphyseal chondrodysplasia caused by mutation(s) in the PTH1R gene, encoding parathyroid hormone/parathyroid hormone-related peptide receptor. This condition is characterized by severe short stature, short bowed limbs, clinodactyly, prominent upper face, and a small mandible. Hypercalcemia and hypophosphatemia due to PTH resistance can appear later in childhood.
The sequence of amino acids along a polypeptide chain.

A population of cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs) specifically reactive to one or more pre-selected viruses, with potential antiviral activity. Upon infusion, after an allogeneic hematopoietic cell transplant (HCT) or in other immunodeficient states, these CTLs help reconstitute viral-specific CTL responses and kill virally infected cells, thereby inhibiting viral infection in immunocompromised patients.
A laboratory test result indicating the presence of HLA-A11 positive cells in a tissue sample.
An indication that survivin expression has been detected in a sample.

label.value: Recurrent Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia/Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma

value.value: The reemergence of chronic lymphocytic leukemia/small lymphocytic lymphoma after a period of remission.

An orally bioavailable androgen receptor (AR) antagonist, with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon oral administration, AR antagonist TRC253 specifically binds to both wild-type and certain mutant forms of AR, thereby preventing androgen-induced receptor activation and facilitating the formation of inactive complexes that cannot translocate to the nucleus. This prevents binding to and transcription of AR-responsive genes, inhibits the expression of genes that regulate prostate cancer cell proliferation, and may lead to an inhibition of growth of tumor cells in which AR is overexpressed and/or mutated. AR is often overexpressed and/or mutated in prostate cancers and plays a key role in proliferation, survival and chemoresistance of tumor cells.

label.value: Recurrent Childhood T Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia

value.value: The reemergence of T-acute lymphoblastic leukemia in childhood after a period of remission.

label.value: Childhood T Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia in Remission

value.value: A finding of T acute lymphoblastic leukemia in childhood that is not growing and responds to treatment.
A clinical test designed to assess episodic memory encoding and retrieval processes in individuals with cognitive impairment.
A questionnaire designed to measure hearing loss or problems experienced by patients who have received treatment for cancer.

label.value: How Often Have Problem with Hearing

value.value: A question about how often an individual had problems with hearing.

The fluid within the amniotic cavity which surrounds and protects the developing embryo. It is initially produced by the amnion and then later by the lungs and kidneys. The amount at term normally varies from 500 to 2000 ml.
A question about how severe an individual's hearing problems are or were.

label.value: How Much Did Hearing Problems Bother You

value.value: A question about how much an individual's hearing problems bothers or bothered them.

label.value: How Much Did Hearing Problems Interfere with Daily Activities

value.value: A question about how much an individual's hearing problems interferes or interfered with their daily activities.

label.value: How Hard to Hear When You Talk to One Other Person in Quiet Place

value.value: A question about how hard it was for an individual to hear when they talked to one other person in a quiet place.

label.value: How Hard to Hear When You Talk to Group of People in Quiet Place

value.value: A question about how hard it was for an individual to hear when they talked to a group of people in a quiet place.

label.value: How Hard to Hear When You Talk to One Other Person in Noisy Place

value.value: A question about how hard it was for an individual to hear when they talked to one other person in a noisy place.

label.value: How Hard to Hear When You Talk to Group of People in Noisy Place

value.value: A question about how hard it was for an individual to hear when they talked to a group of people in a noisy place.

label.value: When in Group of People and Could Not See Speaker, How Hard to Know Where That Person Was

value.value: A question about how hard it was for an individual to know where a person was if they couldn't see them speaking.

label.value: How Often Turn Up Volume Watching TV

value.value: A question about how often an individual has or had to turn up the volume when watching TV.

label.value: How Often Turn Up Volume When Talking on Phone

value.value: A question about how often an individual has or had to turn up the volume when talking on the phone.
The simplest form of an antigenic determinant, on a complex antigenic molecule, which can combine with antibody or T cell receptor.

label.value: When You Talk on Phone, How Hard to Understand What Other Person Was Saying

value.value: A question about how hard it was for an individual to understand what the other person was saying while talking on a telephone.

label.value: How Often Hear Ringing, Buzzing, Whistling Noises Only You Could Hear

value.value: A question about how often an individual heard ringing, buzzing or whistling noises that only they could hear.

label.value: How Severe Were Ringing, Buzzing, Whistling Noises that Only You Could Hear

value.value: A question about the severity of the ringing, buzzing, or whistling noises that only an individual could hear.
